If Aikido is intended as a "non-violent self-defense martial art", then bodybuilding is an even purer expression of those same principles. Becoming huge and muscular without an increased ability to fight, thus preventing fights by appearances alone. Bodybuilding expresses Ahimsa.

"The stronger you grow, the less is the need for aggressive self-assertiveness. This is living your life so that you never harm any creature." Every time someone decides you look too tough to mess with, the principles of non-violence and peacefulness are affirmed in the world.

"Just be normal" is the polemical equivalent of building your house on sand, to use a Biblical expression. A lot considered normal today was weird idiocy before, but certain men persisting managed to force it into the consensus. If one speaks for the consensus, he accepts defeat.

Ernst Junger actually has a good paragraph about how communist governments with a pretend-democracy always made sure to get a number of votes for the fake opposition party, even often printing false votes for them, just to preserve the illusion of their own lack of totality.
An appeal to normalcy at best saves you some time.

My favorite Marty Robbins song is "The Hanging Tree" - a gold prospector gets rich and has a woman fall in love with him, but he's too far consumed by greed. Bandits covet his gold, so they rob him and take him to the hanging tree to hang him; but in the last moment set him free!

He walks off alive and the woman walks with him. He realizes the hanging tree was the Biblical tree of life and he is reborn. Beautiful. The man is alive, he gets the happy ending, the bandits get the gold and are spared of God's wrath for their mercy. Garlands, joy, celebration.

Imagine the clarity. Feeling the cool night air, the noose on your neck, the woman watching, there is no escape, it was all for nothing. But then they set you free. How insignificant the gold must seem. Walking away from your death, indescribable feeling. The Tree of Life.
